<Docs title="Overview">
  <h1>Life</h1>
  <p class="lead">Life is a protocol for agent-legible repos. A <code>.life</code> file in any directory tells an agent what that directory is, what it needs, what it provides, and which commands are safe to run. A repo with a <code>.life</code> at root is <strong>a .life</strong> — a repo that remembers, acts, and evolves.</p>

  <h2>Root contract</h2>
  <pre><code>.life                  # the root manifest — YAML head for machines, Markdown body for agents
.life.lock             # resolved imports — generated by the engine; commit it
.life.engine           # the engine binary — commit it; self-updates via evolve
.genome/               # vendored genes — gitignored, rematerialized each session
.claude/settings.json  # compiled harness settings — the one tracked harness file</code></pre>
  <p><code>.life</code> is the root manifest — YAML frontmatter plus a Markdown body, like every other <code>.life</code> file. The frontmatter is machine-readable; the body explains the repo to agents. Both live in git.</p>
  <p><code>.genome/</code> is the repo's <strong>genome</strong>: the genes it has inherited, vendored locally. It is build output — gitignored, and rematerialized from <code>.life.lock</code> every session by <code>life evolve</code>. The engine bundles no adapters; harness and infra adapters (<code>claude-code</code>, <code>cloudflare</code>, <code>github</code>, …) are genes like any other, loaded from the genome.</p>

  <h2>The primitives</h2>
  <p><strong>A .life.</strong> A repo with a <code>.life</code> manifest at root and the engine at <code>.life.engine</code>.</p>
  <p><strong>Cell.</strong> Any directory with a <code>.life</code> file — the unit of a .life's anatomy. Cells nest: each parent's <code>.life</code> is a map of its children, and a cell grown too large divides into child cells. Adapters are cells. Apps are cells. Same shape, different role.</p>
  <p><strong>Interface.</strong> The YAML frontmatter in a <code>.life</code> file — the machine-readable contract. The Markdown body below it is the directory's README for agents: operational knowledge like "never change the slug," "run this before deploy," "schema lives here."</p>
  <p><strong>Capability.</strong> A namespaced string a cell requires or provides — <code>infra.kv</code>, <code>harness.claude-code</code>, <code>blog.preview</code>. Not a closed enum: a cell that <code>requires</code> what another <code>provides</code> depends on it, and the engine wires the edge.</p>
  <p><strong>Command.</strong> An executable verb a cell declares. Commands can run anything — shell, Node, Python. <code>life &lt;gene&gt; &lt;command&gt;</code> runs one; <code>life</code> alone lists the whole library.</p>
  <p><strong>Gene.</strong> A published cell — a versioned capability in the genepool that any .life can inherit. Engine verbs, session hooks, skills, adapters: all genes. The engine itself is a gene.</p>
  <p><strong>Genepool.</strong> The shared commons at known.life. Every published version stays resolvable forever; a wrong step is corrected by the next publish, never by withdrawal.</p>

  <h2>The verb surface</h2>
  <p>One canonical surface — no aliases, no legacy spellings:</p>
  <pre><code># the repo
life status            # what's here, what's connected, what's missing
life ask &lt;name|path|cap&gt;  # look anything up — local, installed, genepool, engine
life test [dir]        # verify capabilities, secrets, declared tests
life new &lt;dir&gt;          # scaffold a new cell
life evolve            # pull a newer engine, re-pin imports, regenerate the harness

# the genepool
life inherit [src]     # vendor a gene into .genome/ and record the import
life edit &lt;name&gt;       # open a gene in the workbench for a round-trip edit
life fetch &lt;name&gt; &lt;dir&gt;  # (lower-level) pull a gene's source to any dir
life explore           # browse the commons, ranked by installs
life mutate &lt;name&gt;      # publish a gene from its workbench or a dir (lifekey-signed)
life shed &lt;name&gt;        # drop a gene from this .life
life lifekey           # manage the signing identity

# the live world
life connect &lt;provider&gt;   # connect an infra provider
life deploy &lt;dir&gt;          # provision + ship a cell's infra
life data &lt;dir&gt; &lt;kind&gt; &lt;op&gt;  # runtime data — secrets, objects, KV
life teardown &lt;dir&gt; --confirm  # dependency-aware destruction</code></pre>
  <p><code>life ask</code> is the most important. Everything — kernel verbs, local cells, imported genes, the whole genepool — is reachable through that one query, lazily, at the depth the task needs.</p>

  <h2>Capabilities</h2>
  <p>Infrastructure capabilities are semantic. The agent never names vendor products — it requires contracts, and the infra adapter owns the translation:</p>
  <pre><code>infra.compute          # runs code            (→ Worker)
infra.route            # HTTP exposure        (→ workers.dev, custom domain)
infra.datastore        # structured data      (→ D1)
infra.kv               # key-value with TTL   (→ KV)
infra.object_store     # files and blobs      (→ R2)
infra.secret_store     # holds secrets        (→ Worker secrets)
infra.ai               # model inference      (→ Workers AI)
infra.email            # outbound email
infra.agent            # stateful agents      (→ Durable Objects)</code></pre>
  <p>If a cell requires a capability and nothing provides it, <code>life test</code> fails with a specific next step: inherit this gene, connect this adapter. The failing test is the product — it tells a half-wired project exactly what's left.</p>
  <p>The vocabulary is not closed. Domain capabilities (<code>blog.preview</code>, <code>research.report</code>) are ordinary; new <code>infra.*</code> contracts arrive when an adapter learns to translate them.</p>

  <h2>Dependencies</h2>
  <p>Dependencies are just capabilities — there is no separate dependency field. A cell that <code>requires</code> what another <code>provides</code> depends on it:</p>
  <pre><code># api/.life provides a capability
provides:
  api.ready:

# frontend/.life requires it
requires:
  api.ready:       # depends on api being deployed and healthy

# life test frontend/ follows the chain:
# "api.ready not satisfied — run: life deploy api"</code></pre>
  <p><code>life test</code> follows dependency chains transitively. <code>life deploy</code> does not cascade — each cell deploys independently. For a specific gene rather than "anything that provides X," declare it under <code>imports:</code> instead.</p>

  <h2>Private by default</h2>
  <p>Everything is private unless the manifest says otherwise. A deployable's reachability is the top-level <code>route:</code> field — <code>public</code> (open), <code>secure</code> (owner-gated behind a GitHub sign-in; <code>allow:</code> lists the permitted logins), a hostname (custom domain, secure by default), or absent (private — service-binding only).</p>
  <pre><code>route: secure              # workers.dev URL behind the owner gate
allow:
  - your-github-login      # who gets through the gate

commands:
  publish:
    run: bash scripts/publish.sh
    requires_approval: true   # refuses to run without an explicit --approve</code></pre>
  <p>Irreversible commands are gated with <code>requires_approval: true</code> — that is the whole policy layer, and it lives on the command. <code>life teardown</code> always demands <code>--confirm</code>.</p>

  <h2>Cell commands vs adapter commands</h2>
  <p>Cells own business-logic commands — build, test, migrate, seed. Adapters own infra commands — deploy, provision, connect, teardown. The test: "does this command depend on the cell's specific content?" If yes, the cell declares it. If no, the adapter owns it.</p>
  <pre><code># Cell commands (in blog/.life)
commands:
  dev:
    run: pnpm dev
  build:
    run: pnpm build

# Adapter commands (from the infra adapter)
# life deploy blog/    → adapter handles it
# life teardown blog/  → adapter handles it</code></pre>
  <p><code>deploy</code> never appears in a cell's <code>.life</code>. The agent runs <code>life deploy blog/</code> and the engine routes to whatever infra adapter is installed. Change providers and the cell's commands don't move — only the adapter does.</p>

  <h2>The harness layer is compiled</h2>
  <p>Life source produces harness-native files: <code>.claude/</code> (settings, hooks, skills, slash commands), <code>AGENTS.md</code>, <code>.cursor/</code>. These are build output — regenerated by <code>life evolve</code> every session, gitignored (with one exception: <code>.claude/settings.json</code> is tracked so session-start hooks fire on the very first prompt of a cold clone). One-way: source wins. Never hand-edit a generated file — the fix belongs in the gene or the <code>.life</code> that compiles into it.</p>

  <h2>Incremental adoption</h2>
  <p>Life is additive. The installer drops a <code>.life</code> manifest and the engine into any existing repo; nothing breaks, no existing files change. Add <code>.life</code> files to directories one at a time as you touch them — <code>life ask</code> works as soon as one exists.</p>
  <p><code>life test</code> after cloning a .life IS the setup guide — it shows every declared capability that isn't yet connected. No separate onboarding tooling.</p>
</Docs>
